		<!-- message -->
		<div>My letter to Funcom...<br />
<br />
I thought I would leave this off the forums so 1.) a ton of people didn&#8217;t jump on your back , 2.) you didn&#8217;t have to lock the thread because it degraded into a total flame-fest and 3.) hopefully you reply. These are my opinions of your Shadowlands expansion, take them as you will.<br />
<br />
First and foremost I have to say, it&#8217;s very apparent that your Dev team pulled most of it&#8217;s ideas from past Everquest expansions (yes, I&#8217;ve played them all). The sad part being, you picked the worst parts of each to mimic.<br />
<br />
The Everquest expansion &#8220;Ruins of Kunark&#8221; upped the maximum level players could obtain, it also upped the average mob hit points making everything a tad more difficult to kill. But, in theory, you were rewarded more xp when you did take them down. Your version of this was to raise the hit points and damage output of all the mobs in Shadowlands without raising their level, leaving them gray to high level characters, thus yielding no xp.<br />
<br />
Having entire groups of level 200 people die to gray mobs that would give them no xp, should they win, was a brilliant plan. Make sure to give &#8216;Employee of the Millennium&#8217; to whoever came up with that one, upping the risk and diminishing the reward &#8211; excellent work.<br />
<br />
<br />
The next expansion that you borrowed ideas from was &#8220;Shadows of Luclin&#8221;, the expansion that introduced &#8216;Alternate Advancement&#8217; points, or, a way for characters to gain additional power without additional levels. Your perk system would have been a great asset to the game&#8230; had you taken the time to think through the perks/specials to see that there was some semblance of balance.<br />
<br />
Perks were your chance to level a very uneven playing field, they would have been great for giving a boost to neglected professions (those that make up &lt;5% of the player base, even I know which ones they are). But, once again, you blew it. You made Gods out of professions that were already among the top percentile and left the needy classes wanting, yearning, for some sign that you guys even know they exist.<br />
<br />
All professions should be viable in all aspects of play and all perks should be useful no matter what level you are (hi, two xp-related perks for crats!), you guys need to learn that. If there is a class that has &lt;10% of winning a PvP fight vs. anyone in the arena, then that&#8217;s an issue that should be addressed. If there is a class that doesn&#8217;t effect the outcome of a Unique raid, that&#8217;s an issue as well.<br />
<br />
<br />
Another Everquest expansion you looked to for ideas was obviously the &#8220;Planes of Power&#8221;, the previous Everquest expansion which was very well received by the player base, for the most part. Each player who bought the expansion was automatically granted access to Tier 1 planes where they could hunt for xp to acquire additional levels as well as do a quest/kill a big bad guy for access to the next tier. You guys really screwed the pooch on this one.<br />
<br />
In the infinite wisdom of your Dev team they decided that high level players who buy Shadowlands aren&#8217;t given any content to advance them (being level 200 and killing everything I can find for 1xp is fun, really). In order to access any mobs that give xp (or Shadow Knowledge) a level 200 player needs to complete a slew of gray-slaughtering quests requiring you to kill mobs in backyards (kill-stealing from lvl 2 players is good?), Foreman&#8217;s (targeted level 80) and then camp the two mobs that spawn hourly to gain access to the next city. Yes, 48 people max per day gain access to the next city &#8211; good job. In other words, as a level 200 &#8216;Crat I just paid $30 so I could annihilate level 1-80 mobs by the drove and then compete in a kill-stealing fest for hours just to get a chance at seeing some content designed for my level.<br />
<br />
 If it&#8217;s within your power you could see that my account status is now &#8220;Cancelled.&#8221; It&#8217;s what I do when games become not fun to play, because if a game isn&#8217;t fun then what&#8217;s the point? I cancelled Everquest when it became boring. I cancelled Daoc when I hit the level 50 wall and ran out of content and now I&#8217;m canceling AO because I just paid $30 for an expansion that gave me nothing&#8230;<br />
<br />
Honestly, I didn&#8217;t expect immediate gratification with this expansion&#8230; I didn&#8217;t expect all the problems with the current game to be instantly remedied nor did I expect to land in Jobe and be handed my new uber armor of coolness. My low aiming expectation was that I would be presented with new &#8216;challenges&#8217; to overcome with my guild. I don&#8217;t consider farming low-level zones or trying to out damage 25 other lvl200 characters a challenge.<br />
<br />
Elimination of nano/med kits, no yalms, limited ports, no grid, diminished effect new nanos (new &#8216;crat charms are like 2 minutes), useless perks, inaccessible content, broken quests, etc. If I was a new player I would probably love the expansion, it's great eye candy and I could gain xp from all the mobs, but as a level 200 pre-expansion player I feel like I just paid $30 for an empty box. Thanks.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
